e she moved to New York, Tawney had a storied career. She was known for employing an ancient Peruvian gauze weave technique to create a painterly effect that appeared to float in space rather than cling to the wall, as well as for being one of the first artists to blend sculptural techniques with weaving practices and, in the process, pioneered a new direction in fiber art. Despite her prominence on the New York art scene, however, she has only recently begun to receive her due from the greater art world. Accompanying a retrospective at the John Michael Kohler Arts Center, this catalog features a comprehensive biography of Tawney, additional essays on her work, and two hundred full-color illustrations, making it of interest to contemporary artists, art historians, and the growing audience for fiber art. Copublished with the John Michael Kohler Arts Center.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aArt, American-20th century-Exhibitions. 0aCollage-United States-Exhibitions. 0aTawney, Lenore-Exhibitions. 0aTawney, Lenore-Influence. 0aTextile artists-United States-Biography. 0aTextile crafts-United States-Exhibitions. 0aWomen artists-United States-Biography. 7aART / General.2bisacsh  auniverse, universal, fiber, arts, artwork, artistic, display, art, museum, exhibit, exhibition, academic, scholarly, research, 19th, 20th, century, 1950s, 1960s, history, historical, painting, drawing, sculpture, crafts, chicago, new york, urban, city, america, american, united states, usa, weaving, weaver, technique, thread, scene, biography, influence, sculptor, glenn adamson.1 aAdamson, Glenn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGappmayer, Sam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNugent Mangan, Kathleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb